---
import DocsLayout from "~/layouts/DocsLayout.astro";
import Code from "~/components/Code.astro";
---

<DocsLayout
  title="Operators"
  current="operators"
  description="The operator table, precedence, and how to overload per type."
>
  <h1>Operators</h1>

  <p>
    Operators in kex are just methods with symbolic names, attached to a type
    through <code>make</code>. The same symbol can resolve to different
    implementations depending on the receiver.
  </p>

  <h2>Operator table</h2>

  <div
    class="my-6 overflow-hidden rounded-xl border border-[var(--color-line)]"
  >
    <table class="w-full border-collapse text-[14px]">
      <thead class="bg-[var(--color-bg-subtle)] text-left">
        <tr>
          <th
            class="border-b border-[var(--color-line)] px-4 py-2.5 font-mono text-[12px] uppercase tracking-[0.1em] text-[var(--color-faint)]"
            >Operator</th
          >
          <th
            class="border-b border-[var(--color-line)] px-4 py-2.5 font-mono text-[12px] uppercase tracking-[0.1em] text-[var(--color-faint)]"
            >Purpose</th
          >
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody class="font-mono text-[13.5px]">
        {
          [
            ["+", "addition / concatenation"],
            ["-", "subtraction"],
            ["*", "multiplication"],
            ["/", "division"],
            ["== !=", "equality"],
            ["< > <= >=", "comparison"],
            ["&& ||", "boolean logic"],
            ["&", "function / method reference"],
            ["~", "partial application"],
            ["..", "range (1..10)"],
            ["@", "@field shorthand in make"],
          ].map(([op, desc]) => (
            <tr class="border-t border-[var(--color-line)]">
              <td class="px-4 py-2.5 align-top text-[var(--color-accent-strong)]">
                {op}
              </td>
              <td class="px-4 py-2.5 align-top font-sans text-[var(--color-ink-soft)]">
                {desc}
              </td>
            </tr>
          ))
        }
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <h2>Overloading</h2>
  <p>
    Define the operator as a method inside <code>make</code>. Dispatch is by
    receiver type, so <code>Vector2D.+</code> and <code>Vector3D.+</code> can coexist.
  </p>
  <Code
    code={`make Vector2D do
  let +(other: Vector2D) -> Vector2D do
    return Vector2D { x: @x + other.x, y: @y + other.y }
  end

  let *(factor: Float) -> Vector2D do
    return Vector2D { x: @x * factor, y: @y * factor }
  end
end

# Operator sugar resolves through the receiver type:
# unitX * 2.0 + offset`}
    file="overload.kex"
    source="examples/overload.kex"
  />

  <h2>Conversion convention</h2>
  <p>
    A method named <code>to</code> taking a type is the canonical conversion.
    <code>value.to(String)</code> is how values render.
  </p>
</DocsLayout>
